title: People who publish open-source projects, what makes you confident to do that?
text:
Writing some patchy code for some personal project is one thing. But publishing well structured and documented code to the world as an usable package is another thing.

People who do that on a regular basis, what made you capable or confident enough that you can trust your own code to run on other people's machines without the fear of failure?

Was it some specific topic in CS or something that gave you that confidence boost? e.g: some people say I gained confidence after taking an OS course or a Compilers course. Is it like that or is it by reading other people's code?

Ask HN: Which MOOCs in Math/CS are worth still worth taking in 2022?
text: MOOCs doesn't necessarily mean courses on platforms like edX or Coursera. They can include university courses with public materials like videos, notes, assignments, etc.

Ask HN: How have you gotten more paying customers?
text:
What has and hasn't worked for you to acquire more paying customers?

Did you advertise more? Focus on a specific targeted audience or a particular platform?

Did you try to get more users in general to visit your site? Did you try to optimize things with analytics? A/B testing?

Referral incentives?

Did you hire someone or a firm?

Did you just try to make your product better? Or improve you brand?

Do you keep track of all this stuff, and if you do how?
